The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Monday, June 14, 2004  Business Briefs																								 New Delhi, June 13: Petroleum minister Mani Shankar Aiyar today met finance minister P. Chidambaram to give final shape to the pricing policy of petrol, diesel and cooking gas. The two will meet Prime Minister Manmohan Singh tomorrow to get the final nod for revision of petrol and diesel prices. Sources said a new policy will be announced by June 15, the due date for revision of petrol and diesel prices.																								 New Delhi, June 13: A CII-Ascon survey on the services sector showed a 106 per cent growth in the cellular telephony segment in 2003-04 against 90 per cent in the previous year. It is likely to grow by 90-100 per cent in the next six months. Home loan sanctions in the housing finance sector grew by over 30 per cent in 2003-04 against 42 per cent in 2002-03. The hotel industry has also fared well.																								 Mumbai, June 13: Asian Paints is unlikely to enter new countries in the next few years as it plans to consolidate the existing overseas business. It may also exit from operations which have been performing poorly.																								 New Delhi, June 13: The government will soon come out with a comprehensive foodgrain export policy. The policy is virtually ready and will be finalised after necessary fine-tuning by commerce minister Kamal Nath.																								 Sao Paulo, June 13: Ministers of developing nations, including India, attending the Unctad summit, met to reduce mutual trade obstacles and boost their share of global commerce. Commerce minister Kamal Nath said after talks with Brazilian foreign minister Celso Amorim that agriculture was a prime concern for the Indian government.
